<dl id="n54127b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54127b">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54127b"> 127(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> alum <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54127b"><li>FW 86.04 </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/lexd.htm#n54127b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/l39d.htm#n54127b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54127b">MS BL 47476a-194</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:409 <a name="dd10" href="../../FF/fdra/dda.htm#dd10">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/d/dd10.htm#n54127b">Draft: I.4&sect;1.10</a>/2.10</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Now mix up half an ounce of powdered <mark>alum</mark> and half an ounce of powdered sulphate of copper, and having mixed these powders well together with the mortar and pestle, dissolve them in one ounce of hot water, and let the solution cool. <small> H. E. Roscoe, <a name="HERC1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#HERC1"><cite title="source">Science Primer: Chemistry</cite></a> (n.d.) 49</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Alum: A very stringent, whitish, transparent salt crystalising in octohedrons; chemically a double sulphate of aluminium potassium. </mm> </dd></dl>
